data.title: Kristin Chenoweth earns rave reviews for her portrayal of Jackie Siegel in the new musical The Queen of Versailles based on the hit documentary
data.meta_description: Kristin Chenoweth returned to the stage for the first time in nearly a decade, and she's receiving rave reviews already.
data.text:
Kristin Chenoweth returned to the stage for the first time in nearly a decade, and she's receiving rave reviews already.

The 56-year-old Tony-winning actress made her debut as Jackie Siegel in The Queen of Versailles musical at Emerson Colonial Theatre in Boston on Thursday.

She announced back in February that she would both star and produce the musical, which is based on the 2012 documentary of the same name.

The Boston performances will run through August 25, before the musical hits the road to Broadway sometime in 2025.

The reviews are already coming in as well, with many critics heaping praise upon Chenoweth, who could very well be vying for her second Tony Award.

The original documentary followed the one-time billionaire David A. Siegel, who owned a lucrative timeshare company called Westgate Resorts.

He and his wife Jackie were trying to build what would be one of the largest private family homes in America, modeled after the Palace of Versailles in Paris.

The documentary - directed by Lauren Greenfield - chronicled their troubles in getting the project off the ground, and to this date, the massive home is still not completed.

F. Murray Abraham plays Jackie's husband David in the musical, which features music and lyrics from Steven Schwartz, providing a Wicked reunion with Chenoweth.

The musical offers, 'her richest opportunity to date to flex her dramatic muscle,' according to Bob Verini's Variety review, which adds, 'while inspiring the composer-lyricist to the most emotionally affecting score, bar none, of his long career.'

The review adds, 'Chenoweth is courageous and skillful in presenting a protagonist of utter folly, who never quite fathoms where she went wrong. We do, though, and the lesson of false values comes across like a whipcrack.'

'First things first: Kristin Chenoweth is a national treasure, and if you dont agree, you will have to fight us,' begins Peter and Jackie Chinana's review on Boston.com.

'The Wicked actress simply dominates the proceedings from beginning to end, almost never leaving the stage and emanating a level of energy from her 4-foot-11 frame that you simply cannot comprehend without experiencing it in person. Shes like a neutron bomb of charisma,' the review adds.

They even stress that, 'Chenoweths Jackie Siegel deserves to immediately enter the pantheon of unstoppable Broadway musical matrons alongside Streisands Fanny Brice, Mermans Mama Rose, and Lansburys Auntie Mame.'

Jacob Miner from Theaterly admitted he wondered, 'How on Earth was this going to work?' before going into the performance.

He did admit, however, that the production is, 'one of the most bewildering yet entertaining musicals I have seen in recent memory.'

The production from Schwartz, playwright Lindsey Ferrentino and director Michael Arden is said to be still a, 'work in progress,' before it makes its Broadway debut during the 2025-2026 season.
